#week-title("Two", "Sulphur — The Soul Principle")

=== Core Teaching

The second philosophical principle is *Sulphur*. In alchemy, Sulphur represents the
*soul-principle*: the characterizing force, the oily, aromatic, and combustible
nature that gives each substance its individual identity and power.

While Mercury is the same in all living things, Sulphur is what makes one plant
differ from another. In the laboratory, the Sulphur is found in the essential oils
and the colored aromatic fraction — what rises slightly later than the pure
Mercury, or separates as a distinct layer. It is the flammable fraction of the
matter, carrying the "virtue" or specific nature of the plant.

#doctrine[
  _"Sulphur is the soul of a thing, its oily, flammable, characterful nature. It
  is the agent of generation and the seat of the plant's essential power."_
  #align(right)[— TTAO curriculum, synthesising Paracelsus and GCH I]
]

=== Topics This Week

- Sulphur as the soul-principle: definitions and distinctions
- The characterizing force: why plants differ
- Identifying Sulphur in the laboratory: oils and aroma
- Sulphur as the mediator of the World Spirit's specific virtues

#inner-work[
  *The Threefold Breath — Left Channel (Sulphur)*

  After the Third Eye Focus and the Mercury breath, introduce the second stage of
  the *Threefold Breath*.

  *The Practice:*
  Sit. Block the right nostril with the thumb of the right hand. Breathe in slowly
  through the left nostril, imagining the left side of the body filling with warm
  red vapour — the soul, the characterizing fire. Breathe out red vapour.
  Repeat three times.

  This red vapour represents the Sulphur principle. Observe its quality: is it warm?
  Does it feel heavy, dense, or vibrant? Record your observations in the journal.

  *Numerology — The Number 2:*
  Study the number 2 as a living philosophical principle. It is the pair, volatile
  and fixed in their first tension — Sulphur as the second movement, the
  characterizing separation. Two poles appear; they are drawn toward each other and
  repelled simultaneously.
]

